WEBVTT

00:00.534 --> 00:03.037
[***]

00:25.159 --> 00:27.695
[THUNDER CRASHES]

00:30.598 --> 00:31.799
[TIRES SCREECHING]

00:31.799 --> 00:34.668
[DAPHNE, VELMA, SHAGGY
& SCOOBY SCREAMING]

00:36.204 --> 00:39.807
Slow down, Fred.
We wanna get there in one piece.

00:39.807 --> 00:41.142
We're already late.

00:41.142 --> 00:43.277
It's the grand reopening
of the Grimsley Mansion.

00:43.277 --> 00:44.745
And we would have
been there by now

00:44.745 --> 00:47.781
if someone didn't have
to stop us for takeout.

00:47.781 --> 00:49.183
Two someones.

00:49.183 --> 00:50.818
[GIGGLING]

00:50.818 --> 00:53.087
Like, let's dig in.

00:53.087 --> 00:55.323
[BOTH WHIMPER]

00:55.323 --> 00:58.359
Fred, the mansion's been there
for over a hundred years.

00:58.359 --> 00:59.593
It's not going away.

00:59.593 --> 01:01.295
I'm just anxious
to take a crack

01:01.295 --> 01:03.197
at finding
its secret treasure.

01:03.197 --> 01:05.366
Maybe we'll even see
the ghost.

01:05.366 --> 01:06.767
Ghost?
Ghost?

01:06.767 --> 01:08.336
It's supposedly haunted.

01:08.336 --> 01:12.740
We better eat up, Scoob.
This might be our last meal.

01:12.740 --> 01:15.309
Whoa! Oof!

01:15.309 --> 01:18.612
Like, these sandwiches
could use a seatbelt.

01:22.583 --> 01:24.852
MAN:
You may have recognized
Grimsley Mansion

01:24.852 --> 01:26.287
from several movie productions.

01:26.287 --> 01:28.689
There are even films
on its founder,

01:28.689 --> 01:32.092
Augustus Grimsley.
Fascinating man.

01:32.092 --> 01:33.594
For example, did you know

01:33.594 --> 01:35.263
that he was
a Roman history buff,

01:35.263 --> 01:37.998
an amateur astrologist
and a scratch bowler?

01:37.998 --> 01:40.834
Who cares about all that stuff?
What about the treasure?

01:40.834 --> 01:44.272
Yeah, and what about the ghost
that haunts this place?

01:44.272 --> 01:46.507
Gentlemen,
there is no real evidence

01:46.507 --> 01:48.342
that there even is a treasure,
or a gho--

01:48.342 --> 01:50.678
A ghost!
[BOTH WAILING]

01:50.678 --> 01:54.215
[MOANING]

01:54.215 --> 01:56.750
[BOTH YELLING]

01:58.152 --> 02:00.888
[BOTH GRUNT]

02:00.888 --> 02:02.756
[HISSES]

02:02.756 --> 02:04.258
[BOTH SCREAM]

02:07.161 --> 02:08.362
[GRUNTING]

02:08.362 --> 02:09.763
Please, don't drink my blood.

02:09.763 --> 02:12.099
Please,
don't haunt my dreams.

02:12.099 --> 02:13.734
Oh, dear.

02:13.734 --> 02:15.803
We didn't mean to scare you
that much.

02:15.803 --> 02:18.972
I'm Charlie Grimsley,
and that's my brother, Kyle.

02:18.972 --> 02:20.441
We're your hosts.

02:20.441 --> 02:22.710
Hi there.
Enjoying your stay?

02:22.710 --> 02:25.446
We figured folks would expect
a scare while looking for

02:25.446 --> 02:27.448
our great-great-grandfather's
treasure.

02:27.448 --> 02:30.284
So this is all a hoax?
What's going on here?

02:30.284 --> 02:32.820
I told you this was
a terrible idea, Kyle.

02:32.820 --> 02:36.424
The guests want real treasure,
not fake spooks.

02:36.424 --> 02:38.226
But there is no treasure,
Charlie.

02:38.226 --> 02:39.793
What do you mean
"no treasure"?

02:39.793 --> 02:42.062
[CHUCKLES]
My brother is just kidding.

02:42.062 --> 02:45.366
There may be a treasure,
but nobody's ever found it yet.

02:45.366 --> 02:46.567
Maybe you will.

02:46.567 --> 02:48.569
Then join us for breakfast.

02:48.569 --> 02:50.838
Yeah,
there's a waffle bar.

02:50.838 --> 02:52.306
[SIGHS]

02:53.541 --> 02:55.776
I wasn't really scared.

02:55.776 --> 02:58.111
At least we're done
with that lecture.

02:58.111 --> 03:00.281
Look at that.

03:02.916 --> 03:05.185
[THUNDER RUMBLES]

03:05.185 --> 03:07.921
Hey,
the treasure could be inside.

03:12.393 --> 03:14.695
[GROWLING]
[BOTH YELL]

03:14.695 --> 03:16.697
Pulling some more tricks again,
eh?

03:19.099 --> 03:22.202
Phil,
I don't think he's kidding.

03:22.202 --> 03:24.538
[MEN SCREAMING]

03:27.207 --> 03:28.876
[GUFFAWS]

03:28.876 --> 03:31.979
[SCREAMING]

03:31.979 --> 03:34.315
No, come back!

03:34.315 --> 03:35.916
[SCREAMING]

03:35.916 --> 03:37.351
Fred, look out!

03:37.351 --> 03:39.653
[TIRES SCREECH]

03:43.824 --> 03:45.959
[ALL MOANING]

03:47.961 --> 03:49.397
Is everyone okay?

03:49.397 --> 03:51.699
Now we're going to have
to find the treasure.

03:51.699 --> 03:54.101
To pay for
the Mystery Machine.

03:54.101 --> 03:56.103
[ENGINE STALLS]

03:56.103 --> 03:57.971
Hidey ho there, travelers.

03:57.971 --> 04:00.741
Looks like you've got yourself
a smidgeon of car trouble.

04:00.741 --> 04:04.778
Wanda Grimsley, groundskeeper,
mechanic and jill-of-all-trades.

04:04.778 --> 04:06.079
[GIGGLES]

04:06.079 --> 04:07.781
I can handle this.

04:07.781 --> 04:10.050
You can fix
the Mystery Machine?

04:10.050 --> 04:13.554
Well, I think I'm gonna upgrade
you from a smidgeon to a scooch.

04:13.554 --> 04:16.390
But not to worry,
I'll get her purring by morning.

04:16.390 --> 04:18.726
Meanwhile,
my cousins can take care of you.

04:19.892 --> 04:21.995
Monsters!

04:21.995 --> 04:24.565
What? Oh, right. Sorry.

04:24.565 --> 04:27.100
You see?
It's all just for fun.

04:27.100 --> 04:29.269
[BOTH GROAN, THEN THUD]

04:29.269 --> 04:33.006
CHARLIE:
Come on in.
Welcome to Grimsley Mansion.

04:33.006 --> 04:35.543
[***]

04:46.687 --> 04:49.423
DAPHNE:
They were frightened
by a suit of armor?

04:49.423 --> 04:50.891
Yes. It's so silly.

04:50.891 --> 04:53.461
Their imaginations
must have run away with them.

04:53.461 --> 04:55.596
The black knight,
it's gone!

04:55.596 --> 04:57.197
What do you mean gone?

04:57.197 --> 04:59.232
I mean it's gone.
It ran away.

04:59.232 --> 05:00.801
This whole thing's been
a disaster.

05:00.801 --> 05:03.136
There's no treasure,
and I never should have--

05:03.136 --> 05:05.373
Kyle, please. Customers.

05:06.740 --> 05:07.941
Oh, sorry.

05:07.941 --> 05:10.644
Maybe we should hear more
about this black knight.

05:10.644 --> 05:12.480
I might be able
to help you there.

05:12.480 --> 05:14.982
Oh, this is Adam,
our house historian.

05:14.982 --> 05:17.518
Is that a Mensa honors pin?

05:17.518 --> 05:20.020
Why, yes. Yes, it is.

05:20.020 --> 05:21.789
It's very impressive.

05:21.789 --> 05:24.124
You think?

05:24.124 --> 05:25.959
Uh, the, um, story?

05:25.959 --> 05:27.861
Yes, the story.

05:27.861 --> 05:31.031
Well, it's all part of the
legend of Grimsley Mansion.

05:31.031 --> 05:34.735
In the late 1800s, Augustus
Grimsley was a prospector.

05:34.735 --> 05:38.271
A very lucky prospector.

05:38.271 --> 05:41.675
Wealthy beyond his wildest
dreams, and not trusting banks,

05:41.675 --> 05:43.544
he decided to build
a huge mansion

05:43.544 --> 05:45.746
where he would hoard his gold.

05:51.084 --> 05:53.554
He also gave in
to his rapacious appetite

05:53.554 --> 05:55.756
for furnishings
and antiquities,

05:55.756 --> 05:57.558
including his prize purchase,

05:57.558 --> 06:01.228
a beautiful suit
of black armor.

06:01.228 --> 06:04.898
But all this wealth
would take its toll.

06:04.898 --> 06:08.268
Late at night, Gus Grimsley
started to hear noises.

06:08.268 --> 06:11.238
Clanking noises.
[CLANKING APPROACHING]

06:11.238 --> 06:13.807
It could only have been
the suit of armor

06:13.807 --> 06:16.209
marching down the halls.

06:16.209 --> 06:19.279
The next day he found out why.

06:19.279 --> 06:21.715
The armor was once worn
by the black knight,

06:21.715 --> 06:23.684
who tried to steal
his king's riches.

06:23.684 --> 06:25.719
But he was caught
and thrown into a dungeon,

06:25.719 --> 06:27.755
never to be seen again.

06:29.890 --> 06:32.059
Augustus was convinced
the black knight

06:32.059 --> 06:33.461
was now after his gold.

06:33.461 --> 06:35.228
He had the armor taken away,

06:35.228 --> 06:37.765
but he still feared the black
knight would return one day.

06:37.765 --> 06:39.567
So he hid the treasure, vowing:

06:39.567 --> 06:41.469
"Though the ghost
may search forever,

06:41.469 --> 06:43.471
"it's my family
that shall find.

06:43.471 --> 06:45.372
It's only a matter of time."

06:45.372 --> 06:47.941
[ORGAN BLARING]

06:47.941 --> 06:50.778
[BOTH CHUCKLING]

06:50.778 --> 06:53.046
Will you guys
stop fooling around?

06:53.046 --> 06:56.183
Like, sorry.
We're just hungry.

06:56.183 --> 06:58.351
Yeah, hungry.

06:58.351 --> 07:00.688
Kyle, why don't you take them
to the dining room?

07:00.688 --> 07:02.556
We have an all-you-can-eat
buffet.

07:02.556 --> 07:03.824
[BOTH LAUGH]

07:03.824 --> 07:06.994
They had an all-you-can-eat
buffet.

07:06.994 --> 07:09.497
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

07:12.533 --> 07:13.867
I don't understand.

07:13.867 --> 07:15.736
If the black knight
was in storage,

07:15.736 --> 07:17.137
how did it get back here?

07:17.137 --> 07:19.139
Wanda brought it back
in her obsession

07:19.139 --> 07:21.208
to turn this place
into a museum.

07:21.208 --> 07:22.710
And what's wrong with that?

07:22.710 --> 07:25.445
It's not like the treasure hunt
is bringing in the crowds.

07:25.445 --> 07:26.647
Excuse us.

07:26.647 --> 07:28.015
Family squabbles.

07:28.015 --> 07:29.917
What do you want,
Wanda?

07:29.917 --> 07:32.219
Well, it sure would make my life
a lot easier

07:32.219 --> 07:34.822
if we could take those
heavy boxes out of the van.

07:34.822 --> 07:37.224
Oh, those are my monster traps.

07:37.224 --> 07:39.026
Will any of them catch a ghost?

07:39.026 --> 07:40.260
[GIGGLES]

07:40.260 --> 07:43.997
Since we're staying,
might as well get the luggage.

07:43.997 --> 07:45.666
Why don't I
show you around?

07:45.666 --> 07:47.668
This place has such
a splendid history.

07:47.668 --> 07:49.570
That would be sweet.

07:49.570 --> 07:51.805
Good. That would be good.

07:51.805 --> 07:56.309
SHAGGY:
Like, thanks for the buffet
and the midnight snack, Kyle.

07:56.309 --> 07:58.311
What does it matter
if we're out of food?

07:58.311 --> 08:00.447
We don't seem to be getting
any more customers.

08:00.447 --> 08:03.884
My brother thought the lure of
a treasure would bring everyone

08:03.884 --> 08:06.253
and it's only brought disaster.

08:06.253 --> 08:08.488
[ALL GASP]

08:10.524 --> 08:13.594
Huh? Like, what was that?

08:13.594 --> 08:14.895
A booby trap.

08:14.895 --> 08:16.864
Our great-great-granddad
put in a bunch.

08:16.864 --> 08:19.633
Wanda's been trying
to remove them.

08:21.735 --> 08:24.705
Like, Scoob,
you almost saw stars.

08:24.705 --> 08:26.974
Yeah, big ones.

08:26.974 --> 08:29.610
Ah, this whole place is a trap.

08:29.610 --> 08:32.145
Get out while you can.

08:32.145 --> 08:34.313
He seems so sad.

08:34.313 --> 08:36.817
Yeah. Like,
isn't it funny how sadness

08:36.817 --> 08:39.953
can sometimes make you hungry?

08:39.953 --> 08:42.355
Yeah.

08:42.355 --> 08:43.557
Pretzel?

08:43.557 --> 08:44.992
[GROWLS, THEN GRUNTS]

08:44.992 --> 08:46.193
[SCREAMS]

08:46.193 --> 08:48.228
It's the black knight!

08:48.228 --> 08:50.263
[***]

08:50.263 --> 08:53.266
[YELLING]

08:53.266 --> 08:56.303
Shaggy, come on!

09:00.608 --> 09:02.042
Aah!

09:03.577 --> 09:06.113
[***]

09:17.490 --> 09:18.926
[SQUEALS]

09:36.576 --> 09:38.578
[BOTH GROAN]

09:40.447 --> 09:42.182
[BLACK KNIGHT GRUNTS]

09:50.958 --> 09:54.862
Come on, Scoob.
Let's get out of here.

09:56.096 --> 09:58.165
[GRUNTS]

09:59.399 --> 10:01.935
[***]

10:08.642 --> 10:11.912
Phew. I think we lost him,
Scoob.

10:11.912 --> 10:16.016
Yeah.
And look what I picked up.

10:16.016 --> 10:19.186
Like, halvsies, right,
old buddy, old pal?

10:19.186 --> 10:20.553
[SLOBBERING]

10:20.553 --> 10:22.823
What was that?

10:23.824 --> 10:26.593
Hm. Where's my sandwich?

10:26.593 --> 10:28.395
Maybe you ate it.

10:28.395 --> 10:30.864
Maybe someone else ate it.

10:30.864 --> 10:33.266
Like, dude, no way.

10:33.266 --> 10:35.803
And that is my half.

10:38.271 --> 10:39.940
Hmm?

10:39.940 --> 10:41.775
What happened
to the rest of it?

10:41.775 --> 10:43.610
I don't know.

10:43.610 --> 10:45.412
I do.

10:47.848 --> 10:49.783
[SNARLING]

10:49.783 --> 10:52.185
Uh-oh. Shaggy!

10:52.185 --> 10:55.222
Like, hugs are not gonna help.

10:55.222 --> 10:58.058
[BOTH SCREAMING]

11:03.230 --> 11:04.998
ADAM:
Even though Augustus chose

11:04.998 --> 11:06.900
a Victorian sensibility
for the house,

11:06.900 --> 11:08.836
he included
eccentric touches.

11:08.836 --> 11:10.303
Like the death traps.

11:10.303 --> 11:12.505
I hope
I'm not being tiresome.

11:12.505 --> 11:13.941
Jinkies, no.

11:13.941 --> 11:16.844
Coming from you,
it doesn't sound boring at all.

11:18.345 --> 11:20.714
[***]

11:24.484 --> 11:25.753
FRED:
Boo!

11:25.753 --> 11:27.320
Ha. It's just me.

11:27.320 --> 11:28.856
Hey,
did you guys find anything?

11:28.856 --> 11:32.893
I think they have, Fred,
but it isn't clues.

11:32.893 --> 11:35.428
You know,
my great-great-granddaddy

11:35.428 --> 11:37.798
did leave a clue
to the treasure in his will.

11:37.798 --> 11:39.933
So, there really is
a treasure.

11:39.933 --> 11:43.703
Well, Augustus was a bit
of a kidder and crazy to boot.

11:43.703 --> 11:45.072
He said that the clue

11:45.072 --> 11:47.174
would smack you in the kisser
when you saw it.

11:47.174 --> 11:49.276
And I know
where I'd look for it.

11:49.276 --> 11:50.477
In his study.

11:50.477 --> 11:51.779
Come on,
I'll show you.

11:51.779 --> 11:53.046
We'll join you
in a minute.

11:53.046 --> 11:55.315
I still want to explore
the lobby.

11:55.315 --> 11:57.918
Yeah. Uh-huh.

11:57.918 --> 11:59.953
I don't think she thought
you were serious.

11:59.953 --> 12:01.454
The truth is, Adam,

12:01.454 --> 12:04.424
I'd much rather spend
a little more time with--

12:04.424 --> 12:07.027
Jinkies, what's that?

12:07.027 --> 12:10.363
Oh, that's a painting
by Augustus Grimsley.

12:10.363 --> 12:12.299
I didn't know
he was a painter.

12:12.299 --> 12:13.867
He wasn't.

12:13.867 --> 12:15.735
This was the only picture
he ever painted.

12:15.735 --> 12:17.370
Right before he died.

12:17.370 --> 12:20.473
I suppose it has a certain
primitive charm.

12:20.473 --> 12:21.741
What do you see?

12:21.741 --> 12:24.477
I see a clue.

12:25.745 --> 12:27.881
WENDY:
Here's the study.

12:33.153 --> 12:35.322
Are those Roman gladiators?

12:35.322 --> 12:38.525
Yep. Uncle Augustus sure loved
his Roman history.

12:38.525 --> 12:40.760
Well, I gotta keep working.

12:40.760 --> 12:42.930
Happy hunting.

12:45.532 --> 12:47.767
[SHAGGY AND SCOOBY YELLING]

12:49.269 --> 12:50.838
What's wrong now?

12:50.838 --> 12:53.740
We're being stalked
by a hungry hibiscus.

12:53.740 --> 12:55.742
And the black knight too.

12:55.742 --> 12:57.044
You saw the black knight?

12:57.044 --> 12:59.279
Yeah. Like,
someone's gotta tell that dude

12:59.279 --> 13:02.149
that knights
are the good guys.

13:02.149 --> 13:03.350
Ah!

13:05.318 --> 13:08.822
Oh, no!
The Romans are roaming!

13:14.727 --> 13:15.996
[GRUNTING]

13:15.996 --> 13:18.431
We're locked in! Ah!

13:24.237 --> 13:25.873
[YELLS]

13:28.976 --> 13:32.612
They're running on tracks.

13:32.612 --> 13:35.348
If I could just time this right.

13:35.348 --> 13:37.918
[GRUNTS]

13:40.854 --> 13:42.822
Oh, there you are.

13:42.822 --> 13:45.192
Have I got something
to show you.

13:45.192 --> 13:47.827
According to the position
in the picture,

13:47.827 --> 13:50.463
this is Sirius,
the morning star.

13:50.463 --> 13:53.200
Morning star?
What could it mean?

13:53.200 --> 13:54.667
SCOOBY:
We saw a star.

13:54.667 --> 13:57.337
A big star.

13:58.671 --> 14:00.240
Just down this hall.

14:01.508 --> 14:03.843
Here it is.

14:03.843 --> 14:06.313
[ALL SCREAM]

14:10.017 --> 14:12.819
Like, sorry.

14:12.819 --> 14:14.487
Hmph!

14:14.487 --> 14:15.889
A morning star.

14:15.889 --> 14:17.257
That's what
they used to call

14:17.257 --> 14:19.692
a spiked club like this
in medieval times.

14:19.692 --> 14:22.795
Hey, there's an opening.

14:22.795 --> 14:24.597
I can't see anything.

14:24.597 --> 14:28.668
Wait. In the picture,
the star was shining, right?

14:28.668 --> 14:31.504
Right.

14:31.504 --> 14:34.041
[***]

14:46.653 --> 14:49.189
[GROANS]

14:50.790 --> 14:52.025
[GASPS]

14:52.025 --> 14:54.161
The key to the treasure.

14:55.462 --> 14:56.896
ALL:
Huh?

14:56.896 --> 14:58.231
[FAINT RUMBLING]

14:58.231 --> 15:00.667
Like, what do you hear,
Scoob?

15:02.970 --> 15:04.904
[WHIMPERING]

15:04.904 --> 15:06.239
Check it out.

15:06.239 --> 15:09.176
It's crazy,
old Great-Grandpa Grimsley.

15:09.176 --> 15:11.511
Like,
there's something written here.

15:11.511 --> 15:14.381
"This thing runs,
but cannot walk,

15:14.381 --> 15:17.217
"sometimes sings,
but never talks,

15:17.217 --> 15:20.087
"lacks arms, has hands,

15:20.087 --> 15:23.423
lacks a head, but has a face."

15:23.423 --> 15:24.691
It's a riddle.

15:24.691 --> 15:26.159
It's not very funny.

15:26.159 --> 15:28.928
Let's see.
It runs and it sings.

15:28.928 --> 15:30.998
And it has a face and hands.

15:30.998 --> 15:32.365
A clock!
A clock!

15:32.365 --> 15:35.135
Jeepers, didn't Augustus
also say something about:

15:35.135 --> 15:37.137
"'Tis only a matter
of time?"

15:37.137 --> 15:38.705
It's in the clock tower.

15:38.705 --> 15:40.673
Come on.

15:40.673 --> 15:42.809
[SCOOBY WHIMPERS]

15:42.809 --> 15:47.014
Like, don't worry, buddy!
I'll find a ladder!

15:47.014 --> 15:49.116
[CONTINUES WHIMPERING]

15:50.650 --> 15:53.153
[GROWLS]

15:56.389 --> 15:59.526
FRED:
I don't see any door
that fits this key.

15:59.526 --> 16:01.494
Maybe it's
not for a door, Fred.

16:01.494 --> 16:04.331
Maybe it's a key
to the clock.

16:13.606 --> 16:14.741
A-ha!

16:16.576 --> 16:18.078
It fits.

16:18.078 --> 16:20.613
[CLOCK WHIRRING]

16:22.949 --> 16:25.085
The clock hands are moving.

16:26.753 --> 16:29.289
[BELL TOLLS]

16:37.564 --> 16:39.032
It's unlocked.

16:39.032 --> 16:41.868
[GRUNTS]

16:41.868 --> 16:43.936
You did it!
You found it!

16:43.936 --> 16:45.472
We found it.

16:47.440 --> 16:49.042
Hey!

16:49.042 --> 16:50.777
DAPHNE:
No!

16:50.777 --> 16:52.612
[GRUNTING]

16:52.612 --> 16:53.846
We're trapped.

16:53.846 --> 16:57.650
[GUFFAWS]

16:57.650 --> 17:00.420
SHAGGY:
Like, I hope there's a snack
machine up there.

17:00.420 --> 17:03.390
'Cause this is one long climb.

17:03.390 --> 17:04.723
Aah!

17:06.093 --> 17:07.960
[***]

17:07.960 --> 17:10.530
[SCREAMING AND GRUNTING
CONTINUES]

17:21.241 --> 17:23.143
[BOTH GROANING]

17:29.816 --> 17:31.284
[GUN COCKS]

17:31.284 --> 17:35.188
Like, time to net the knight,
Scoob.

17:39.726 --> 17:41.261
[GROANS]

17:43.029 --> 17:44.697
Yikes!

17:52.139 --> 17:54.241
Over there, Scoob!

17:57.410 --> 17:59.746
[ENGINE SPUTTERS, THEN STARTS]

18:03.283 --> 18:05.017
Dude, what are you doing?

18:05.017 --> 18:07.720
Black knight.

18:07.720 --> 18:09.256
Oh, no!

18:13.460 --> 18:16.129
[GROWLS]
[SCREAMS]

18:21.668 --> 18:23.803
[BLACK KNIGHT GROANS]
Hm?

18:29.976 --> 18:31.311
[BLACK KNIGHT SCREAMS]

18:31.311 --> 18:35.282
SCOOBY: Bye-bye!
Scooby, I can't see!

18:38.318 --> 18:40.653
[GRUNTING AND BANGING]

18:49.762 --> 18:54.000
It worked. These bars
are worth their weight in gold.

18:54.000 --> 18:56.769
[SHAGGY AND SCOOBY WHIMPERING]

19:00.072 --> 19:03.176
Do you think we lost him?

19:03.176 --> 19:04.911
[***]

19:04.911 --> 19:08.515
Hey, Scoob,
does this hallway look familiar?

19:08.515 --> 19:10.317
Yeah.

19:16.756 --> 19:18.591
Huh.

19:19.959 --> 19:21.761
[GROWLS]

19:21.761 --> 19:25.198
Uh-oh.
Like, I think he knows.

19:25.198 --> 19:28.134
[GROWLS]

19:28.134 --> 19:30.537
[LAUGHS]

19:32.272 --> 19:34.274
[BANGING APPROACHING]

19:36.909 --> 19:40.012
Oh, no.

19:40.012 --> 19:42.181
[YELLS]

19:47.287 --> 19:49.689
Aah!

19:54.427 --> 19:58.197
You did it.
You caught the black knight.

19:59.232 --> 20:01.067
[GRUNTING]

20:01.067 --> 20:02.569
What is that?

20:02.569 --> 20:04.937
WENDY:
No, Eugene! Come here.

20:04.937 --> 20:06.506
Who's a good fly trap?

20:06.506 --> 20:09.309
Who's a good baby boy? You are.

20:09.309 --> 20:11.143
Yes, you are.

20:11.143 --> 20:12.512
He's harmless.

20:12.512 --> 20:14.881
One of Uncle Augustus'
exotic plants.

20:14.881 --> 20:16.082
Raised him from a seed.

20:16.082 --> 20:19.151
Didn't he, baby?
Yes, he did.

20:19.151 --> 20:22.855
Okay, now let's see
who the black knight really is.

20:26.359 --> 20:27.827
[BOTH GASP]

20:27.827 --> 20:29.996
Like, it's nobody?

20:29.996 --> 20:32.265
It's somebody all right.

20:32.265 --> 20:33.500
ADAM:
Kyle?

20:33.500 --> 20:35.568
Good heavens,
what's going on?

20:35.568 --> 20:37.069
It's pretty evident,
Charlie.

20:37.069 --> 20:39.606
Your brother wanted
all the gold for himself.

20:39.606 --> 20:42.675
That's why he was so insistent
that there was no treasure.

20:42.675 --> 20:44.511
When Wanda brought
the black knight armor

20:44.511 --> 20:46.713
back to the mansion,
he saw his opportunity

20:46.713 --> 20:49.582
to scare away anyone who might
come looking for the gold.

20:49.582 --> 20:51.884
Oh, and my plan
would have worked too,

20:51.884 --> 20:54.754
if it hadn't been
for you meddling kids.

20:54.754 --> 20:55.988
And your dog.

20:55.988 --> 20:57.657
And that stupid plant.

20:57.657 --> 21:00.026
[GROANS]
Oh, you're not stupid.

21:00.026 --> 21:02.862
Don't you listen to him.
Don't you do it.

21:05.532 --> 21:07.567
CHARLIE:
You know,
deep down I never believed

21:07.567 --> 21:10.269
there was a real treasure,
but since you found it,

21:10.269 --> 21:12.405
I guess you should be
the ones to have it.

21:12.405 --> 21:13.706
That's okay,
Charlie.

21:13.706 --> 21:15.475
We know it belongs
to your family.

21:15.475 --> 21:17.310
We're just happy
to have found it.

21:17.310 --> 21:19.579
Well, if you're gonna be
that generous,

21:19.579 --> 21:21.748
then the car repair
is on the house.

21:21.748 --> 21:24.417
[GIGGLES]

21:24.417 --> 21:26.018
I wanna come with you,
Velma.

21:26.018 --> 21:27.420
I really do.

21:27.420 --> 21:29.956
But I can't leave the mansion.
They need me here.

21:29.956 --> 21:31.458
And my friends need me.

21:31.458 --> 21:35.061
Sometimes it's such a curse
to be the smart one.

21:35.061 --> 21:37.063
We're on our way, Velma.

21:42.001 --> 21:43.370
Where's Scooby?

21:43.370 --> 21:47.674
Like, he's sharing his Scooby
Snacks with his new friend.

21:50.477 --> 21:54.080
Scooby-Dooby-Doo!

21:54.080 --> 21:56.849
[GIGGLES]

21:58.217 --> 22:00.753
[***]
